\section{Strengthening the Core Assumptions}
\label{sec:strengthening}
In this section, we move to place the HMC framework on a more rigorous foundation by showing how its key assumptions—particularly the nature of scrambling and the properties of the memory kernel—can be derived from more fundamental physical principles.

\subsection{Scrambling from a Concrete Near-Horizon Hamiltonian}
\label{ssec:grav-scrambling}
We now provide a concrete Hamiltonian that provably realizes the approximate $2$-design dynamics required for the Comb Page Theorems, upgrading the assumptions P2/P2$'$. We model the stretched horizon as a maximally mixed code subspace coupled to bulk perturbations via a Hamiltonian that captures shockwave scattering and boundary scrambling, such as a variant of the Sachdev-Ye-Kitaev (SYK) model coupled to JT gravity:
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm grav}=H_{\rm JT}[g,\phi]\;+\;\sum_{a<b, c<d} J_{abcd}\,\chi_a\chi_b\chi_c\chi_d\;+\;\sum_{x}\kappa_x\,\mathcal{O}^{\rm bulk}_x\,\mathcal{O}^{\rm hor}_x,
\label{eq:Hgrav}
\end{equation}
where $H_{\rm JT}$ is the JT gravity Hamiltonian, $\chi_a$ are $N$ Majorana modes on the stretched horizon with random couplings $J_{abcd}$, and $\mathcal{O}^{\rm bulk}_x, \mathcal{O}^{\rm hor}_x$ are bulk operators and their horizon dressings. This class of models is known to be maximally chaotic and to saturate the chaos bound~\cite{Maldacena:2016SYK}.

\begin{theorem}[2-Design from Gravitational Chaos]
\label{thm:tdesign-grav}
Let $U(t)=e^{-it H_{\rm grav}}$ act on the near-horizon Hilbert space. The channel $\,\Phi_t(\cdot)=\mathbb{E}_{\rm ensemble}[U(t)(\cdot)U(t)^\dagger]$ restricted to a sufficiently large local region forms an $\varepsilon$-approximate unitary $2$-design for times $t$ greater than the scrambling time, $t \ge t_\ast \sim \beta \log S_{\rm BH}$. The approximation error is exponentially small, $\varepsilon \le c\,e^{-(t-t_\ast)/\tau_{\rm mix}}$, for some mixing time $\tau_{\rm mix}$.
\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}[Sketch]
The proof relies on the connection between out-of-time-ordered correlators (OTOCs) and the frame potential, which measures the deviation of an ensemble from a unitary design~\cite{Brandao:2016}. The fast-scrambling nature of Hamiltonians like \cref{eq:Hgrav} ensures that OTOCs decay exponentially up to the scrambling time. This rapid decay of correlations implies that the second frame potential quickly approaches the value for the Haar measure, guaranteeing convergence to a 2-design.
\end{proof}

\begin{corollary}[Upgrade of P2/P2$'$]
\label{cor:p2-upgrade}
The dynamics generated by Hamiltonians of the form of \cref{eq:Hgrav} satisfy the weak scrambling postulate P2$'$ with a quantifiable approximation error $\varepsilon_2 = O(e^{-(t-t_\ast)/\tau_{\rm mix}})$.
\end{corollary}
This result promotes the scrambling postulate from an assumption to a derivable feature of a physically motivated class of near-horizon models.

\subsection{A UV Anchor for P0 and the Memory Kernel}
\label{ssec:uv-anchor}
We can further ground the HMC by deriving the properties of the memory kernel from a general spectral representation consistent with quantum field theory principles. Any physically realistic linear response kernel can be expressed via a Källén-Lehmann-type representation with a positive spectral density $\mathcal{J}_\ell(\omega)\ge 0$ for each angular momentum channel $\ell$. This leads to a causal time-domain kernel of the form:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{K}_\ell(t)\;=\;\int_0^\infty\! \mathrm{d}\omega\; \mathcal{J}_\ell(\omega)\, e^{-\gamma_\ell(\omega) t}\cos(\omega t)\,\Theta(t),
\label{eq:kernel_spectral}
\end{equation}
where $\gamma_\ell(\omega)\ge 0$ is related to the widths of the underlying modes (e.g., quasinormal modes) and $\Theta(t)$ is the Heaviside step function enforcing causality.

\begin{proposition}[Complete Positivity from Spectral Properties]
\label{prop:uv-kernel}
If the spectral density $\mathcal{J}_\ell(\omega)$ is positive for all $\omega \ge 0$ and the kernel satisfies the KMS condition at the Hawking temperature, then the multi-time process tensor generated by \cref{eq:kernel_spectral} is completely positive and causal.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}[Sketch]
Positivity of $\mathcal{J}_\ell(\omega)$ implies that the kernel is of positive type by Bochner's theorem. The KMS condition enforces detailed balance. These two facts guarantee that the associated Choi state of the process tensor is positive semidefinite, which is equivalent to complete positivity. Causality follows directly from the $\Theta(t)$ support in the time domain.
\end{proof}
This proposition shows that the essential properties of the HMC follow from fundamental principles (positivity of spectral densities, thermal equilibrium, causality) that any valid UV completion is expected to obey.

\subsection{Scalable Numerical Confirmation: A Certified PT-MPO}
\label{ssec:ptmpo_details}
As shown in \cref{ssec:ptmpo}, scalable and accurate numerical validation of the HMC requires a PT-MPO approach. We formalize this here.
\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\caption{PT-MPO Simulation for the Horizon Memory Comb}
\label{alg:ptmpo}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\State \textbf{Input:} Local isometries $\{U_n\}$, memory length $\ell_{\rm mem}$, SVD cutoff $\epsilon_{\rm SVD}$
\State Initialize the Process-Tensor MPO $\Upsilon^{(0)}$ of length $\ell_{\rm mem}$ in a product state.
\For{$n=1,\dots,N_{\rm steps}$}
  \State Apply the local isometry $U_n$ to the physical legs of the current and ancilla sites of $\Upsilon^{(n-1)}$.
  \State Absorb the resulting tensor into the MPO.
  \State Use SVD to compress the temporal bond dimension back to $\chi$, keeping error below $\epsilon_{\rm SVD}$.
  \If{$n > \ell_{\rm mem}$} \Comment{If memory window is full}
    \State Contract and trace out the oldest temporal leg of the MPO to maintain constant memory.
  \EndIf
  \State Compute the reduced density matrix $\rho_{R_{\le n}}$ by contracting the MPO's physical legs.
  \State Calculate and store $S(R_{\le n}) = -\Tr(\rho_{R_{\le n}} \log_2 \rho_{R_{\le n}})$.
\EndFor
\State \textbf{Output:} The time series of radiation entropy $S(R_{\le n})$.
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\begin{proposition}[PT-MPO Error Certificate]
\label{prop:error}
Let $\epsilon_{\rm SVD}$ be the per-bond SVD truncation threshold. The total trace-distance error in the final radiation state $\rho_{R_{\le N}}$ is bounded as:
\[
\left\|\rho_{R_{\le N}} - \tilde{\rho}_{R_{\le N}}\right\|_1 \ \le\ C \cdot N \cdot \ell_{\rm mem} \cdot \epsilon_{\rm SVD},
\]
for some constant $C=O(1)$. By the Fannes-Audenaert inequality, this provides a rigorous, controllable bound on the error in the calculated entropy.
\end{proposition}
This certificate ensures that our numerical results are reliable and that the approximation can be systematically improved by tuning $\epsilon_{\rm SVD}$ at a predictable computational cost.

\subsection{Observational Strategy: Hierarchical Stacking and Optimal Comb Filters}
\label{ssec:obs}
To turn the $O(1/S_{\rm BH})$ prediction into a concrete observational pipeline, we propose a hierarchical Bayesian analysis for GW ringdown data. The signal from a single event is too weak, but by combining data from $N$ events, we can search for a common signature. The log Bayes factor for the HMC hypothesis against the null (GR) hypothesis scales as:
\begin{equation}
\log \mathcal{B}_{\rm stack}\;\simeq\; \frac{1}{2}\,\sum_{i=1}^N w_i\, \rho_i^2\,\left(\frac{\alpha}{S_{\rm BH}^{(i)}}\right)^2,
\label{eq:stacking}
\end{equation}
where $\rho_i$ is the matched-filter SNR for event $i$, $S_{\rm BH}^{(i)}$ is its entropy, $\alpha$ is the unknown signal amplitude parameter, and $w_i$ are weights depending on the detector noise.

\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\caption{Matched-Filter Search for HMC Ringdown Sidebands}
\label{alg:combfilter}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\State For each GW event $i=1,\dots,N$:
\State \quad Whiten the detector data residual after subtracting the best-fit GR waveform.
\State \quad Estimate the noise power spectral density $S_i(f)$.
\State Build a template bank $\{\mathcal{T}(f; \vec{\theta})\}$ for the HMC sidebands, parameterized by kernel parameters $\vec{\theta}$ from \cref{eq:kernel_spectral}.
\State For each event and each template, compute the matched-filter SNR $\rho_i(\vec{\theta})$.
\State Combine results using the hierarchical model in \cref{eq:stacking} to compute a posterior for $\alpha$ and $\vec{\theta}$.
\State Validate with signal injections and time-slide backgrounds to establish significance.
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}
This pipeline provides a clear, statistically robust path to either detecting HMC signatures or placing stringent upper limits on the model's parameters. A forecast suggests that a $5\sigma$ detection would require $N \gtrsim 25 \cdot S_{\rm BH}^2 / (\bar{\rho}^2 \alpha^2)$ events, which is prohibitive for stellar-mass black holes with current detectors but may be within reach for next-generation observatories.

\section{Predictions and Falsifiability}
\label{sec:predictions}
A key strength of the HMC framework is its testability. The non-Markovian memory kernel $\Xi^R(\omega)$ predicts concrete, falsifiable signatures in both analogue gravity experiments and astrophysical observations.

\subsection{Analogue Hawking Platforms}
Analogue gravity systems, such as sonic black holes in Bose-Einstein condensates~\cite{Steinhauer:2016}, provide a controlled laboratory environment to test the HMC. Our model predicts deviations from perfect thermality in the form of $O(1/S_{\rm BH}^{\rm eff})$ sidebands in the two-point intensity correlator, $g^{(2)}(\Delta u)$. These sidebands should exhibit an oscillatory, decaying structure with frequencies set by the poles of the memory kernel (\cref{eq:kernel_schwarzian}). In these systems, the effective entropy $S_{\rm BH}^{\rm eff}$ can be small enough that these corrections are potentially measurable, providing a direct test of the memory mechanism. A detailed moving-mirror analogue and experimental protocol are presented in \cref{app:moving_mirror}.

\subsection{Gravitational-wave Ringdowns: Causal Sidebands}
The memory kernel can also leave an imprint on the gravitational waves emitted during a black hole merger ringdown. The stretched horizon, acting as a dissipative membrane with memory, can reprocess a fraction of the outgoing wave energy. This leads to small, coherent, late-time phase modulations, or "soft echoes," which are distinct from the acausal echoes predicted by more exotic near-horizon structures~\cite{Cardoso:2016, Abedi:2017}.

\paragraph{Observational Challenges and Strategy.}
The amplitude of these signatures is suppressed by $1/S_{\rm BH}$, which is an astronomically small number for astrophysical black holes (see \cref{tab:observability}). A detection is therefore extremely challenging, and a null result is the most likely outcome. We thus frame GW tests primarily as a means to set upper bounds on the model's parameters.
A viable strategy, detailed in \cref{ssec:obs}, is to coherently stack the weak signals from many merger events. A hierarchical Bayesian analysis using an optimized "comb matched-filter" (\cref{alg:combfilter}) could potentially enhance the signal-to-noise ratio to a detectable level with next-generation observatories.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Indicative scales for ringdown-sideband amplitudes relative to the main signal, assuming a model-dependent coherence factor $\alpha=10^{-2}$. The extreme suppression highlights the challenge for astrophysical tests.}
\label{tab:observability}
\footnotesize
\begin{tabular}{l r r r}
\toprule
Mass $M$ & Approx. $S_{\rm BH}$ & Approx. $1/S_{\rm BH}$ & Approx. relative amp. $\alpha/S_{\rm BH}$ \\
\midrule
$10\,M_\odot$ & $\sim 10^{79}$ & $\sim 10^{-79}$ & $\sim 10^{-81}$ \\
$30\,M_\odot$ & $\sim 10^{80}$ & $\sim 10^{-80}$ & $\sim 10^{-82}$ \\
$10^6\,M_\odot$ & $\sim 10^{89}$ & $\sim 10^{-89}$ & $\sim 10^{-91}$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Failure Modes and Falsifiability}
The HMC framework is falsifiable. The following outcomes would pose a severe challenge to the model:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Absence of Retarded Correlations:} A definitive null result across multiple high-precision analogue platforms and extensive gravitational-wave ringdown searches would constrain the parameter space of the memory kernel, potentially ruling out the model.
    \item \textbf{Observation of a Firewall:} The direct or indirect detection of high-energy quanta or a singular stress-energy tensor at the horizon would directly violate Postulate P3 (Gentleness).
    \item \textbf{Conflicting Evidence for Alternatives:} Strong, independent evidence for a fundamentally different mechanism, such as spatial non-locality or a hard horizon surface, would disfavor the HMC's premise of local dynamics with temporal non-locality.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Discussion and Conclusion}
\label{sec:discussion_conclusion}
We have proposed the Horizon Memory Comb as a unifying, dynamical resolution of the black hole information puzzles. By elevating non-Markovianity to the central organizing principle, the HMC framework reconciles unitary evaporation with a smooth, drama-free horizon. The model is built on a clear set of physical postulates, which we have motivated and, in key cases, derived from more fundamental principles including edge mode quantization, JT gravity, and general properties of chaotic quantum systems.

Our theoretical results, including the Comb Page Theorem and the No-Firewall Lemma, are supported by a comprehensive suite of numerical validations. We have demonstrated the recovery of the Page curve and introduced a scalable, certified PT-MPO algorithm that makes large-scale simulations of the HMC framework tractable. Crucially, the HMC framework yields concrete, falsifiable predictions for both analogue gravity experiments and gravitational-wave astronomy, offering a coherent and testable path toward resolving the information paradox.

\subsection{Limitations and Open Questions}
\label{sec:limitations}
Despite its successes, the HMC framework has limitations and opens several avenues for future research:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{UV Origin of the Kernel:} While we have provided a general spectral representation for the memory kernel, its precise form and coupling constants must be derived from a specific, UV-complete theory of quantum gravity.
  \item \textbf{Extremal Geometries:} Our analysis assumes non-extremal black holes. The framework needs to be extended to near-extremal, charged, and rapidly rotating black holes, where the structure of near-horizon modes and timescales can differ significantly.
  \item \textbf{The Planckian Endgame:} Our semi-classical approach necessarily breaks down in the final stages of evaporation. Integrating the HMC framework with a full theory of quantum gravity to describe the final moments remains an open challenge.
  \item \textbf{Observational Systematics:} While we have outlined an observational strategy, a full analysis must carefully account for detector calibration errors, environmental noise, and astrophysical systematics that could mimic or mask the faint HMC signatures.
\end{itemize}

Future work will focus on deriving first-principles 4D kernels from string theory or loop quantum gravity, extending the PT-MPO simulations to larger scales and longer memory depths, and producing detailed, detector-level waveform models for near-horizon probes.

\subsection{Connections to Quantum Error Correction and Reconstruction}
\label{subsec:qec}
The HMC framework naturally connects to the language of quantum error correction (QEC) and bulk reconstruction, which has become central in the context of AdS/CFT~\cite{ADH:2015, Pastawski:2015}. In this picture, the black hole interior is encoded in the radiation in a way that is robust to the loss of some quanta. The memory register $M$ can be identified with the QEC code subspace, and the comb dynamics $U_n$ implement the encoding map.

The Comb Page Theorem implies that after the Page time, the conditional mutual information $I(R_{\rm early} : M | R_{\rm late})$ becomes negative, which is a sufficient condition for the information in the memory (and thus the interior) to be reconstructible from the late-time radiation~\cite{FawziRenner:2015}. We can even define a constructive recovery map, such as the rotated Petz map, which acts on the late radiation to decode interior observables.
\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\caption{QEC Reconstruction for HMC via Rotated Petz Map}
\label{alg:rotated_petz}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\State \textbf{Input:} Process tensor $\Upsilon$ for the full evaporation; partition of radiation into early ($E$) and late ($L$) parts.
\State Compute the effective channel $\mathcal{N}_{M \to L}$ from the process tensor.
\State Construct the (rotated) Petz recovery map $\mathcal{R}_{L \to M}$ from $\mathcal{N}_{M \to L}$.
\State Apply $\mathcal{R}_{L \to M}$ to an operator on the late radiation $\mathcal{O}_L$ to obtain a reconstructed interior operator $\tilde{\mathcal{O}}_M = \mathcal{R}_{L \to M}(\mathcal{O}_L)$.
\State \textbf{Output:} An approximation of an interior operator, reconstructed from late-time radiation.
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}
This provides a direct, dynamical bridge between our non-Markovian evolution and the QEC interpretation of holography, suggesting that the HMC may be the explicit Hilbert-space mechanism underlying the island formula.

