\section{Robustness Bounds under Weak Scrambling}
\label{app:robustness}
Here, we sketch the proof of the Comb Page Theorem under the weak scrambling postulate P2$'$. The standard decoupling proof relies on averaging over the Haar measure. When the unitary ensemble is only an $\varepsilon_2$-approximate 2-design, the decoupling arguments still hold but acquire an error term proportional to $\varepsilon_2$. Specifically, the trace distance between the actual radiation state and the maximally mixed state is bounded by a sum of terms capturing the system size mismatch and the design error.

Furthermore, P2$'$ assumes the scrambler is local, acting on a lightcone of size $\ell_{\rm scr}$. Operators outside this lightcone are only affected exponentially weakly. This introduces another error term of order $e^{-\ell_{\rm scr}/\xi}$, where $\xi$ is the correlation length of the state. Finally, the spectral deviation $\varepsilon_{\rm spec}$ bounds how much the single-step entropy production can differ from the thermal expectation. Combining these errors via a triangle inequality and summing over the $n$ steps of the evaporation leads to the bound presented in \cref{thm:comb-page-weak}. The logarithmic correction arises from the use of the Fannes-Audenaert inequality to convert the trace distance bound into an entropy bound.

